To compute the area, we need to know the points of intersection of the
curves. For \emph{y=4x} and \emph{xy=1}, i.e. point \emph{P}, this is
when \emph{x(4x) = 1}, i.e. $x^2 = 1/4$. Equivalently \emph{x=1/2}, and
\emph{y=2}.

For \emph{y=x} and \emph{xy=1}, i.e. point \emph{Q}, this is \emph{(x,y)
= (1,1).}

Thus, the total area is

\begin{align*}
A &= \int_0^{1/2} (4x-x)\,dx + \int_{1/2}^1\left(\frac1{x}-x\right)\,dx \\
&= 3 \int_0^{1/2} x\,dx + \int_{1/2}^1 \frac1{x}\,dx - \int_{1/2}^1 x\,dx \\
&= \left.\frac32 x^2\right|_0^{1/2} + \left.\ln x\right|_{1/2}^1 - \left.\frac{x^2}2\right|_{1/2}^1 \\
&= \frac38 + \underbrace{\ln 1}_{= 0} - \underbrace{\ln(1/2)}_{=-\ln 2} - \left(\frac12 - \frac18\right) \\
&= \frac38 + \ln 2 - \frac12 +Â \frac18 = \ln 2.\end{align*}
